content:
Use Hierarchical Aggregation in CRM Analytics to sum measures across multilevel data. For example, you can roll up revenues, assets, or liabilities for companies and their subsidiaries. Or, you can roll salesperson data up the management chain to see aggregates by team, region, area, and beyond.

Hierarchical Aggregation requires rows with an ID and a parent ID. Many rows can have the same parent ID, or the parent ID can be empty. Some rows can even share an ID, such as a record with multiple parents.

You can also use the optional roll up percentage to apply percentage splits to allocate portions to different parents, such as commission among members of the sales team.

In a Data Prep recipe that already has at least one Input node, select the Add Node button and choose Aggregate. Turn on Hierarchical Aggregation and add at least one Aggregate, such as the sum of a measure or count of rows.

Specify the Record ID Column and Parent ID Column. The parent ID identifies which record each row rolls up to. Not every record needs to have a parent, for instance if itâ€™s at the top of a hierarchy.

Optionally, select a Roll-Up Percentage Column to apply a percentage split.

To add the Hierarchical Aggregation to the recipe, click Apply and save the recipe.

With hierarchical aggregation you can automatically sum values at each level of the relationship instead of calculating values manually.

Example 1: Simple hierarchy such as region and country.
WITHOUT HIERARCHICAL AGGREGATION
Record ID	Parent ID	Amount
A01		100	A01	600
A02	A01	200	A02	200
A03	A01	300	A03	300
A04		400	A04	400

WITH HIERARCHICAL AGGREGATION
Record ID	Amount
A01	1200
A02	800
A03	300
A04	400

Example 2 Intermediate hierarchy such as an org chart.
WITHOUT HIERARCHICAL AGGREGATION
Record ID	Parent ID	Amount
A01		100	A01	1200
A02	A01	200	A02	800
A03	A01	300	A03	300
A04	A05	400	A04	400
A06	A02	600	A05	400
A07		700	A06	600
			A07	700

WITH HIERARCHICAL AGGREGATION
Record ID	Amount
A01	1200
A02	800
A03	300
A05	1300
A06	600
A07	1700

Example 3 Complex hierarchy such as subsidiary ownership with split percentages.
WITHOUT HIERARCHICAL AGGREGATION
Record ID	Parent ID	Amount	Percentage
A01		100	A01	1375
A02	A01	200	1.00	A02	350
A03	A01	300	0.50	A03	1850
A03	A10	300	0.50	A04	1290
A04	A05	400	1.00	A05	1290
A06	A02	600	0.25	A06	600
A06	A03	700	0.75	A07	700
A07				A08	890
A08	A04		1.00	A09	900
A09	A08		0.10	A10	1925
A10				A11	1100
A11	A03		1.00	A12	1100

WITH HIERARCHICAL AGGREGATION
Record ID	Amount
A01	1375
A02	350
A03	1850
A04	1290
A05	1290
A06	600
A07	1700
A08	890
A09	900

title: Hierarchical Aggregation in CRM Analytics
